{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1948101501/0882.xml":{"full_text":"The Editor's Page\nIt's a Good Investment\nHEN Montana farmers and ranchers\nW\ngo to the polls Nov. 2 they will, like\na& other citizens, have an opportunity to\nexpress their convictions by placing an X\nbefore the names of the candidates of their\nTV.\u00bb-\u00bb- win \u00abI\u00ab\u00ab V, to tv*, nnnnrhmitv to\nsmTn adS invesU\nment in a project that has already demon\nstrated its ability to produce returns of\nseveral thousand percent in terms of added\nchoice.\nagricultural income and to buy a further\ninsurance for the agricultural future of\nMontana,\nThese opportunities will be undramati\ncally labeled on the ballot as referendums\n51 and 52.\nReferendum 51 proposes to increase the\nmillage levy on taxable property in the\nstate, for the support of the six units of the\nuniversity system for the next 10 years,\nfrom the present \"3% mills to 6 mills. Refer\nendum 52 proposes to issue $5,000,000 of\nbonds to construct buildings on university\ncampuses. It has been estimated that the\nmaximum cost of both these measures to\na taxpayer with $10,000 assessed property\nvalue would be only $15 a year. That would\nbe assuming that the full 6 mills would be\nlevied and that the building loans would\nbe paid off in the shortest possible time.\nActually, the cost might be somewhat less.\nAny careful investor looks over the bal\nance sheet of the enterprise in which he is\nconsidering investing before he puts out\nany cash. What does the balance sheet of\nthe Greater University of Montana show?\nFirst of all, the farmer and rancher will\nbear in mind that the\nMontana agricultural\nim its 15 research and\nservice departments and laboratories, and\nthe Montana extension service are part of\nthe university system. New varieties and\nnew methods worked out by the experi\nexperiment station wi\nBoom Psychology \"Busted\"\nT HAS often been said that we have our\nboom and bust cycles chiefly because we\nhave a boom and bust psychology. It is all\nin our minds. Times are good because we\nthink they are and business flows freely;\ntimes become bad because we become pan\nicky and business stops. During the last\ndepression attempts were made to break\nI\ndepression attempts were made to break\nthe deadlock by assurances that prosperity\nwas just around the corner.\nWhatever merit there may be in this\npsychology angle it is certain that over-op\ntimism during previous booms caused seri\nous distress when reaction set in, and lack of\nthis false optimism is one of the most en\ncouraging differences between present con\nditions and those following World war 1.\nIn 1919, as now, prices for farm products\nwere high. At that time everyone expected\nthem to remain so and expanded farm ex\npenditures accordingly. Witfiin a little\nmore than a year prices had dropped 50\npercent and, with the heavy farm debt\nsituation that had developed, many farm\ners were put through the economic wringer.\nThe same thing happened again in the\n1930s.\nA federal reserve bank report points out\nment station and the assistance in putting\nthese into practical use and operation given\nby the extension service have added mil\nlions to the annual agricultural income,\nDoes the operator raise barley? He prob\nably has had his cut of the $4,000,000 which\nthe new varieties, Compana and Glacier,\nare estimated to have added to the worth of\n\u00ab>e 1948 crop alone. Does he produce wool?\nNew knowledge of shrinkage averages, re\nducing the cut from 64 to 57 percent, should\nbring him a share of the minimum of\n$1,000,000 annually which can be saved in\nmarketing. Does he produce beef? The\nj _\nintroduction of crested wheatgrass on his\nranges have given him a return of $11 an\nacre in beef production. Does he raise\nwheat? New methods developed have in\ncreased his returns a minimum of $3 an\nacre.\nThen there are the services in soil testing,\nseed testing, veterinary analyses, poultry\nand dairy research and extension. All this\nresearch and service has its immediate\ncash value, but it will be increasingly im\nportant in future years as margins of opera\ntions narrow and constantly improved prod\nucts and methods become necessary to show\nprofits. Their continuance will be an insur\nance of the stability of Montana agriculture.\nBut aside from these direct cash consider\nations, Montana farm and ranch families\nwill take satisfaction in the returns from\ntheir investment in all branches of the\n\nsi y, Missoula, Montana School of Mines,\nButte; Montana State Normal college, Dil\nIon; Montana State college, Bozeman; Nor\nthern Montana college, Havre, and Eastern\nuniversity system, Montana State univer\nMontana Normal school, Billings. The rural\nvoter knows what the educational advan\ntages offered by these units mean to the\nyouth and future of Montana. As a shrewd\noperator and a progressive citizen he sees\nreferendums 51 and 52 as good investments.\nthat the situation now is similar in some\n\nrespects in that farm production has again\nexpanded even more than in 1919 and\nagain exports are declining.\n'If it were not for three very important\nfactors,\" says the report, \"the level of farm\nprices now and in the next several months\nmight be expected to follow the 1920-21\npattern. These factors are:\n\"Various government price support pro\ngrams, such as commodity loans and pur\nchases.\n\"Subsidized exports, such as army feed\ning of occupied territories, the EGA pro\ngram and others,\n\"Low farm debts and high financial re\nserves.\"\n\"This latter is important,\" the report con\ntinues, \"because farmers as a group are not\nunder too great pressure to sell as they were\nin 1920, when debts were high. In other\nwords, farm lands and farm commodities,\nfor the most part, are now in 'strong\nhands'.\"\nDuring these favorable years farmers and\nranchers have not been guilty of a foolish\noptimism but have carried the recollec\ntion of the 1920s and 1930s and have been\ninclined to behave as though a recession\nwere just around the comer. This has not\nbeen a foolish pessimism but a wholesome\nattitude that in itself has been a potent\nfactor in postponing the development of a\nrecession.\nStraws in the Wind\nLarger feed supplies are likely to reduce\nthe meat supply in the near future rather\nthan to increase it. Cattle and hog feeders\nwill keep livestock on feed longer periods\nw n a ^tas^rce^Tte deS/toZS\ning W\u00dc1 mean more pounds Q f meat fi na ll y>\nbut that time probably will be after Jan.\n1, 1949.\nPrie\u00ae* would b\u00ab from 12 to 20 per\ncent higher than they are now if food sup\nplies h d nQt M they hav\nprincipally from improved techniques, a\nColorado A&M college expert asserts,\nAmerican farmers have pushed food pro\nduction steadily upward despite great han\ndicaps, until today the caloric tonnage is 40\npercent above the prewar level.\nNew hormones have been found that has\nten the maturity of food plants. It may\nmean that crops formerly unadaptable to\nshort seasons can now be produced in north\nern areas. It may even mean that grains\ncould be rushed to maturity before the\ndeadlines of July drouth periods.\n\nA new beverage milk and an ice cream\nmade from sweet cream buttermilk are an\nnounced by the USD A bureau of dairy in\ndustry. Both products are said to be highly\nnutritious and offer a new outlet for plenti\nful and cheap nonfat milk solids.\n\nAn over-all cut of 15 percent in the na\ntional potato acreage for 1949 and support\na t \u00dfo percent of parity appears to be the pic\nture for the coming production year. Flax\nsupport will be at 90 percent of parity,\nwhich will mean a price of close to $4 a\nbushel, Minneapolis basis,\n\nNow that farm prices are trending down\nward while operating costs are still mov\ning up, good management is more impor\ntant than ever.\nHow can you purchase more satisfaction\nwith some of those bushels of wheat you\nraised this season than by exchanging them\nfor a pressure water system?\n\nM\nMontana cattle slaughter so far this year,\naccording to the bureau of agricultural\neconomics, is down 18 percent from the\nsame period last year. Weights, however,\nhave averaged 964 pounds as compared to\n933 for last year, so that the reduction in\nmeat production is only 15 percent.\nMontana Farmer-Stockman\n\u2014COVERS MONTANA AND NORTHERN WYOMING\u2014\nOFFICE: 1\u00c41 4th SU N., Great Falte. Mentone\nLESTER COLE\nDON R. BOSLEY\nLARRY GILL\nJERRY LESTER\nEditor and Mininr\nAssistant Editor\nLivestock Editor\nRevins Reporter\nDepartment Editors: AMY MARTIN, Rural Homes Depart\nment: DR. HOWARD WELCH, Veterinary Department:\nRALPH D. MERCER, Soils and Crops: H. E. CUSHMAN,\nPoultry; I. W. DICKERSON, Farm Mechanics; DR. JOHN\nW. HOLLAND, Thoughts on Life: GILBERT GUSLRR,\nMarket Analyst.\nAdvertising Representatives: Western Associated Fares\nPapers\u2014 CHICAGO 4: Fred Tool, National Adv Manaser,\n28 E Jackson. NEW YORK 18; John W. For, Manaser. 508\nFifth Avenue: SAN FRANCISCO S: J. J. Mattua, Man\naser. 787 Sharon Building.\nMember of Associated Farm Papers, Aadit Boreas of\nCirculations and Agricultural Publishers Association\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE\u201413 for flvo year\u00bb. I* for tilrea\nrears. $1 for one year: Canadian, one year. 12.00.\nRENEWALS AND CHANGES\u2014II the date on your label\nIs not changed within three weeks after sending In\nyour remittance, please write us. If you wish a change\nin address, give both new and old postofflcea.\nADVERTISING\u2014Pull Information regarding advertising\nrates etc., sent on application. Subscribers are requested\nto mention promptly to as any advertiser who laite\nto live up to bis advertising agreement.\nVsL M, No. 4","height":"15954","width":"11106"}}
